Consider the perfectly well-conditioned system:
\[
\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ 1 & 1 \end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}
\]

The unique solution is $x_1 = 1$, $x_2 = 1$. But Gaussian elimination 
requires computing $m_{21} = a_{21}/a_{11} = 1/0$—undefined!

**Solution:** Swap rows first:
\[
\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}
\]
Now the system is already upper triangular and solves easily.

Consider:
\[
\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 100000 \\ 1 & 1 \end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix} 100000 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}
\]

Partial pivoting: $\max(|2|, |1|) = 2$, so no swap. But $100000 \gg 2$ in 
the first row, making the first row "naturally larger."

Scaled partial pivoting: $s_1 = 100000$, $s_2 = 1$. 
Ratios: $|2|/100000 = 0.00002$, $|1|/1 = 1$. Choose row 2 as pivot!
